Reason through the design of a code duplication detection system that must balance correctness, performance, and actionability for a multi-language codebase. The core tension is that not all duplication is bad: some duplication is intentional (copied boilerplate, test fixtures, configuration), some is accidental (copy-pasted logic that should be extracted), and some is necessary (language-specific idioms that look similar but cannot be safely merged). A naive detector that flags all repetition generates so much noise that developers disable it.

Think through the following design decisions carefully. First, what is the right minimum clone size? A threshold of 6 lines catches real duplication but generates many false positives in test files. A threshold of 15 lines misses short but important duplicated business logic. Should the minimum size differ by context (test files versus production code) and by clone type? Second, how should a token-based clone detector handle the normalization step for Type 2 clones (same structure, different identifiers)? Normalizing all identifiers to a placeholder catches more structural clones but loses the ability to distinguish semantically different clones with similar structure. What is the right normalization policy for string literals, numeric literals, and identifiers separately? Third, how should the detector handle the file exclusion problem: generated code (protobuf outputs, migration files, vendored dependencies) will have high duplication but fixing it is not appropriate. What is the right mechanism for excluding these contexts — path patterns, file header comments, or something else? Fourth, the actionability problem: when two clones are found, the report should ideally suggest what extraction would look like. For Type 1 clones this is straightforward. For Type 2 clones the extracted function would need parameters. For Type 3 clones the extraction may require significant restructuring. How should the duplication report communicate the effort required to eliminate each clone pair, and when should it recommend tolerating the duplication instead?
